France's newly elected
President Emmanuel Macron
offered this appeal

02:43.333 --> 02:45.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
reinforced by
speaking in English.

02:45.833 --> 02:50.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EMMANUEL MACRON, French
President: To all
scientists, engineers,
entrepreneurs, responsible

02:50.500 --> 02:55.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
citizens who were disappointed
by the decision of the president
of the United States, I want

02:56.966 --> 03:01.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to say that they will find
in France a second homeland.

03:01.766 --> 03:06.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I call on them, come
and work here with us.

03:09.866 --> 03:14.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Both leaders said
they wouldn't renegotiate the
deal, as President Trump said

03:14.733 --> 03:16.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
he was prepared to do.

03:16.800 --> 03:21.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Meanwhile, in Brussels,
officials from China,
the world's largest
emitter of greenhouse

03:23.266 --> 03:26.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
gases, met with European
counterparts and reaffirmed
their commitment.

03:28.300 --> 03:30.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Support also poured in from
the U.S. corporate world.

03:30.700 --> 03:35.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
More than two dozen
companies, including
oil giant Shell, Apple,
Facebook and Morgan Stanley,

03:38.066 --> 03:42.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
had signed a letter urging
Mr. Trump to stay in the pact.

03:42.100 --> 03:47.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Separately, General Electric
CEO Jeff Immelt and Tesla
chief Elon Musk argued the move

03:48.800 --> 03:51.433 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
