some of those claims.

11:22.133 --> 11:25.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The first thing the president
said was, we will get out of
Paris, but maybe we will strike

11:25.566 --> 11:27.566 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a better deal.

11:27.566 --> 11:31.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: Begin negotiations
to reenter either the Paris
accord, or a really entirely

11:34.000 --> 11:39.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
new transaction, on terms that
are fair to the United States.

11:39.000 --> 11:43.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: But leaders
from many of the other 195
nations in the deal said there

11:43.466 --> 11:46.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
was no appetite
for renegotiation.

11:46.300 --> 11:49.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
French President Emmanuel Macron
summed up the view of many.

11:49.500 --> 11:53.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
EMMANUEL MACRON, French
President (through translator):
He committed an error for the

11:53.066 --> 11:58.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
interests of his country,
his people and a mistake for
the future of our planet.

11:59.300 --> 12:01.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We will not renegotiate
a less ambitious accord.

12:01.533 --> 12:03.533 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
There is no way.

12:03.533 --> 12:07.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: President
Trump also implied that the
Paris accords are binding on the

12:07.500 --> 12:08.500 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
United States.

12:08.500 --> 12:11.033 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
But they're not.

12:11.033 --> 12:14.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The entire accord relies
on voluntary commitments,
so many argue that, if
the president wanted

12:14.233 --> 12:19.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to stay in and wanted to
change the U.S.' commitment,
he's largely free to do so.

12:20.666 --> 12:22.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Jason Grumet is the president
of the Bipartisan Policy Center.

12:22.766 --> 12:25.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
®MD-BJASON GRUMET, President,
Bipartisan Policy Center: What
was unique about the Paris

12:25.800 --> 12:30.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
accord is that it was
essentially a collection
of 200 individual promises.

12:30.000 --> 12:33.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Every country came forward
and made a unique commitment.

12:33.233 --> 12:36.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And each country has
the capacity to reassert
it own commitments.

12:36.600 --> 12:41.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think it's entirely
reasonable for President
Trump to say, I'm
uncomfortable with this

12:43.533 --> 12:46.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
aspect of what the United
States committed and, therefore,
we're going to take a somewhat

12:46.166 --> 12:48.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
different approach.

12:48.266 --> 12:52.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The U.S. would obviously have
much more capacity to influence
the choices, views and efforts

12:53.733 --> 12:55.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of others if we were part
of that conversation.

12:55.833 --> 12:59.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Another one
of the main complaints the
president made: This will hurt

12:59.133 --> 13:01.633 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
U.S. jobs.

13:01.633 --> 13:05.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: Compliance
with the terms of the
Paris accord and the
onerous energy restrictions

13:07.200 --> 13:10.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it has placed on the United
States could cost America as
much as 2.7 million lost jobs by

13:15.033 --> 13:20.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
2025, according to the National
Economic Research Associates.

13:22.433 --> 13:25.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The
international mining
giant Peabody Energy
applauded the president's

13:25.666 --> 13:27.666 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
move.

13:27.666 --> 13:31.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
"Peabody believes that this
path cannot be followed without
substantially impacting the

13:33.633 --> 13:36.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
U.S. economy, increasing
electricity costs on families
and businesses, and requiring

13:38.700 --> 13:41.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the power sector to rely
on less diverse and more
intermittent energy sources."

13:43.866 --> 13:46.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But others point out that
study about lost jobs that the
president cited was written

13:46.800 --> 13:51.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by groups that are opposed to
the Paris accords, and that they
used some worst-case predictions

13:52.966 --> 13:55.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
that other economists
believe are unrealistic.

13:55.366 --> 13:59.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Asked about this on NBC this
morning, Commerce Secretary
Wilbur Ross defended using these

13:59.600 --> 14:01.766 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
studies.

14:01.766 --> 14:03.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILBUR ROSS, U.S. Commerce
Secretary: Well, you should
know what your downside is.

14:03.133 --> 14:05.200 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's an important thing.

14:05.200 --> 14:10.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And particularly when you're
trying to forecast events many
years out into the future, it's

14:11.333 --> 14:13.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
very, very difficult
to be accurate.

14:13.833 --> 14:18.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Roberton
Williams is an economist with
Resources For the Future, a

14:18.066 --> 14:20.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
nonpartisan group that
studied the Paris accord.

14:20.200 --> 14:24.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERTON WILLIAMS, Resources
For the Future: What we have
modeled in terms of job effects

14:24.866 --> 14:29.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is that it's much more of a
job shift than it is job loss
or net job gain, that jobs

14:31.833 --> 14:36.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
go away in coal, and you get
more jobs in some green jobs,
renewable energy, small effects

14:39.033 --> 14:40.266 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
elsewhere.

14:40.266 --> 14:42.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But there is not a big
-- it is not a big drop.

14:42.300 --> 14:46.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The president
also argued that while coal
jobs in the U.S. would suffer,

14:46.066 --> 14:51.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
other nations like India
and China, the other
two major global carbon
polluters, would have

14:51.000 --> 14:52.966 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a free hand.

14:52.966 --> 14:57.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: China will be
able to increase these emissions
by a staggering number of

15:00.533 --> 15:01.733 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
years, 13.

15:01.733 --> 15:04.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They can do whatever
they want for 13 years.

15:04.933 --> 15:07.000 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Not us.

15:07.000 --> 15:09.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: But Jason
Grumet said it wasn't true that
other countries can do whatever

15:09.833 --> 15:11.800 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
they want.

15:11.800 --> 15:15.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JASON GRUMET: The assertion that
the United States fundamentally
disabled our economy,

15:17.766 --> 15:21.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
while other countries move
forward with absolutely no
concern is just not accurate.

15:22.666 --> 15:26.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think that the U.S. made
some meaningful commitments.

15:26.166 --> 15:29.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think it's perfectly
reasonable for President Trump
to suggest that we want to

15:29.866 --> 15:31.966 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
reconsider those commitments.

15:31.966 --> 15:36.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Renegotiating the United States'
commitments is absolutely right.

15:39.033 --> 15:41.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it is an exaggeration to
suggest that other countries
were not sincere or did not

15:41.200 --> 15:43.300 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
make meaningful commitments.

15:43.300 --> 15:46.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The president
also touched on an issue that
is central to the Paris accord,

15:46.200 --> 15:51.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
which is: Can it achieve
its stated goal of
preventing the planet
from warming an additional

15:52.566 --> 15:55.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
two degrees Celsius, or
about 3.6 degrees Fahrenheit?

15:55.366 --> 15:59.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Yesterday, the president
said the accord will barely
affect global temperatures.

15:59.400 --> 16:04.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: Even if the Paris
agreement were implemented in
full, with total compliance

16:06.433 --> 16:10.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
from all nations, it is
estimated it would only
produce a two-tenths
of one degree -- think

16:12.700 --> 16:17.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of that, this much -- Celsius
reduction in global temperature
by the year 2100, tiny,

16:23.833 --> 16:25.766 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
tiny amount.

16:25.766 --> 16:30.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Again,
there's a question of where this
data comes from, and whether

16:31.866 --> 16:33.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the president's statement
accurately reflects the science.

16:33.966 --> 16:38.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The White House said the
president was citing this study
done by researchers at MIT.

16:38.933 --> 16:42.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But MIT said today the president
misused their research.

16:42.233 --> 16:47.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN REILLY, MIT: The president
really took the study out of
context by pointing out this

16:47.000 --> 16:48.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
two-tenths of a degree.

16:48.500 --> 16:50.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: John Reilly
is co-author of this MIT report.

16:50.466 --> 16:54.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN REILLY: This was the
incremental effect of Paris
compared to the previous accord.

16:54.666 --> 16:59.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Altogether, if we look at
past policy, we think that's
reduced warming by a full degree

17:01.833 --> 17:03.866 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Celsius.

17:03.866 --> 17:07.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We still have more we need
to do to get to the ultimate
goal of two degrees, but Paris

17:09.066 --> 17:11.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
is an important
step along that way.

17:11.100 --> 17:15.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: And Roberton
Williams argues that even a
minor slowing of global warming

17:15.066 --> 17:17.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
can hold off some
major destruction.

17:17.433 --> 17:22.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERTON WILLIAMS: Even
small changes in temperature,
even small reductions
below that what we get

17:24.000 --> 17:27.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
without any action, can make
a big difference in how much
damage there is to the world.

17:27.933 --> 17:32.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, even tenths of a degree
can make a difference of
hundreds of billions of dollars.

17:32.166 --> 17:35.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Yesterday,
the president said the U.S.
will formally withdraw from

17:35.800 --> 17:37.266 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the accord.

17:37.266 --> 17:41.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's a process that could take
several years to complete.

17:43.733 --> 17:47.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The climate
decision raises question about
the economy, and so does today's

17:55.466 --> 17:58.033 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
jobs report.

17:58.033 --> 18:01.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In it, the unemployment
rate dropped to its
lowest point in 16 years,
causing some economists

18:03.333 --> 18:06.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to raise the prospect of what
they call full employment.

18:06.200 --> 18:09.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But job growth seems to
have slowed considerably.

18:09.600 --> 18:13.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
With the latest revisions,
the economy is generating an
average, we're told, of about

18:13.266 --> 18:16.633 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
120,000 net new jobs each month.

18:16.633 --> 18:21.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
To get some insight into all of
this, we're joined from Chicago
by Diane Swonk, an economist

18:21.466 --> 18:23.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
who runs her own firm.

18:23.633 --> 18:25.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Diane Swonk, welcome
back to the program.

18:25.733 --> 18:29.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, overall, what do you
make of these jobs numbers
for the month of May?

18:29.166 --> 18:31.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DIANE SWONK, Founder, DS
Economics: Well, certainly,
they were a disappointment.

18:31.933 --> 18:36.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That said, we don't need to
generate as many jobs as we once
did to keep the unemployment

18:36.166 --> 18:38.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
rate steady or even fall.

18:38.233 --> 18:42.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Of course, the unemployment
rate itself fell for the wrong
reasons in the month of May.

18:42.133 --> 18:45.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And that is that
the participation
rate fell yet again.

18:45.200 --> 18:49.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're seeing more people retire
out of the labor force and men
in particular didn't participate

18:49.900 --> 18:52.000 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
as much in the month of May.

18:52.000 --> 18:54.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is something we like
to see moving in reverse
at this stage of the game.

18:54.833 --> 18:58.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: When you say,
Diane, that the country, you
said we don't need to generate

18:58.333 --> 19:01.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
as many jobs as we once
did, what do you mean?

19:01.133 --> 19:04.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DIANE SWONK: Well, basically,
the labor force isn't
growing very rapidly anymore.

19:04.900 --> 19:08.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And even though the economy
is very subdued in its growth
at 2 percent, you just don't

19:08.933 --> 19:13.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
need to create very many jobs
to absorb those workers coming
into the labor force and keep

19:13.333 --> 19:15.033 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
the unemployment
rate going down.

19:15.033 --> 19:18.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
We have actually seen
job growth slow and the
unemployment rate fall.

19:18.233 --> 19:21.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that is because we're near
what we call full employment.

19:21.333 --> 19:23.400 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That sounds good in terms.

19:23.400 --> 19:27.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
What it really means
in economist terms and
for the Federal Reserve
is nearly all of those

19:27.400 --> 19:32.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people who are employable
or are employed or who are
looking for a job are now sort

19:32.066 --> 19:37.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of either between jobs because
they wanted to be between
jobs or are just coming into

19:39.000 --> 19:41.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the labor force, but it's
not a lot of extra slack
in the U.S. economy.

19:41.066 --> 19:44.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That said, it doesn't mean all
those people who want a job
in the U.S. economy or have

19:44.766 --> 19:47.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
dropped out and are not
looking can actually get a job.

19:47.233 --> 19:51.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Diane, you were
telling us earlier today that
the focus on jobs obscures

19:51.600 --> 19:55.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the need to look at
raising skill levels.

19:55.400 --> 19:56.400 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Talk about that.

19:56.400 --> 19:58.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DIANE SWONK: Exactly.

19:58.400 --> 20:01.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One of -- there are two reasons
why we saw the wage gains
slow in the month of May from

20:01.933 --> 20:03.200 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
a year ago.

20:03.200 --> 20:04.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It is only up at a
2.5 percent rate.

20:04.700 --> 20:06.866 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This is something we like to see
going in the other direction.

20:06.866 --> 20:09.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
If you are near full employment,
wages should be accelerating.

20:09.433 --> 20:14.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One reason is because
millennials are replacing
older baby boomers
and they're paid less.

20:14.400 --> 20:16.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
That is not a bad reason
for wage growth slowing.

20:16.666 --> 20:21.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The other reason is that we are
seeing many employers out there
dip further into lower-skilled

20:23.700 --> 20:25.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
workers, but instead of paying
them more, they are actually
investing in training, because

20:25.933 --> 20:30.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they don't have the skills
necessary to do the jobs they
have or they are leaving job

20:30.800 --> 20:33.133 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
positions open.

20:33.133 --> 20:36.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The shortages in construction
are particularly acute
and manufacturing, which
actually contracted.

20:38.933 --> 20:41.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We still have over 300,000
jobs that aren't filled just
because people don't have the

20:41.933 --> 20:44.033 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
right skills.

20:44.033 --> 20:47.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So we would do much better to
enhance the skills of those out
there who are on the sidelines

20:47.933 --> 20:52.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and not participating right
now to bring them back in, than
just give them tax cuts to cut

20:53.566 --> 20:55.533 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
low wages.

20:55.533 --> 20:58.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And very quickly,
finally, Diane, we took note
yesterday when President

20:58.133 --> 21:03.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Trumped talked about the country
having created, I think, he
said a million jobs since the

21:03.866 --> 21:05.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
election last November.

21:05.066 --> 21:06.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Does that reflect
what's been going on?

21:06.866 --> 21:09.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
DIANE SWONK: It is
a bit of a stretch.

21:09.166 --> 21:12.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We have created 800,000 jobs
since the beginning of the year.

21:12.966 --> 21:17.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you want to do it
since he's been president,
it's about 600,000 jobs.

21:17.200 --> 21:21.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, depending on how he wants
to count, I think it is a
little early for him to take

21:21.200 --> 21:25.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
credit one way or the other,
and might be careful what he
wants to take credit for in

21:25.000 --> 21:27.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
